1 (b) (1) The General Assembly intends to promote the interests and well–being
2 of each resident of a facility.
3 (2) It is the policy of this State that, in addition to any other rights, each
4 resident of a facility has the following basic rights:
5 (i) The right to be treated with consideration, respect, and full
6 recognition of human dignity and individuality;
7 (ii) The right to receive treatment, care, and services that are
8 adequate, appropriate, and in compliance with relevant State and federal laws, rules, and
9 regulations;
10 (iii) The right to privacy;
11 (iv) The right to be free from mental and physical abuse;
12 (v) The right to notice, procedural fairness, and humane treatment
13 when being transferred or discharged from a facility;
14 (vi) The right to participate in decision making regarding transitions
15 in care, including a transfer or discharge from a facility;
16 (vii) The right to expect and receive appropriate assessment,
17 management, and treatment of pain as an integral component of the patient’s care;
18 (viii) The right to be free from physical and chemical restraints, except
19 for [restraints]:
20 1. RESTRAINTS that a physician authorizes for a clearly
21 indicated medical need; OR
22 2. SEDATIVES, ANTI–ANXIETY MEDICATION, A BED RAIL,
23 OR A GERI CHAIR ORDERED OR AUTHORIZED BY A PRESCRIBER, AND USED IN
24 COMPLIANCE WITH THE ORDER, FOR A PATIENT RECEIVING HOSPICE CARE;
25 (ix) The right to receive respect and privacy in a medical care
26 program; and
27 (x) The right to manage personal financial affairs.
28 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
29 October 1, 2025.

